[center][size=5][b]OSF - native animation & scene framework for Starfield.[/b][/size][/center]

[center][b][color=#f08a24]Work in progress - report anything broken[/color][/b][/center]

[line]

[center][img]https://staticdelivery.nexusmods.com/mods/4187/images/17457/17457-1782620284-856347009.png[/img][/center]
OSF is a native animation and scene engine for Starfield, inspired by [b]OStim [/b]and[b] NAF[/b]. It plays animation on actors, keeps multiple characters in sync, anchors them in the world, controls the camera, and runs whole scenes in a data-driven, json based authoring flow.

You can use it directly in-game: an [b]animation browser[/b] to look through everything installed and play it on yourself or nearby NPCs, and an [b]emote wheel[/b] for one-key quick emotes. Or drive it from other mods: you describe a whole scene in a json data file and OSF runs it at runtime, instead of scripting timings and animation events in papyrus yourself.

The engine itself carries no content; the installer offers two optional starter packs - the game's own animation library, and an emote pack for the wheel.

[center][img]https://staticdelivery.nexusmods.com/mods/4187/images/17457/17457-1782620284-2144773043.png[/img][/center]
[list]
[*]In-game [b]animation browser[/b] ([font=Courier New]F10[/font]): search the full catalog, pick a cast from the crosshair or a nearby-actor scan, launch on furniture, drag to orbit the camera, and manage running scenes[/*]
[*][b]Emote wheel[/b] (default [font=Courier New]B[/font], rebindable): radial quick emotes for you or the NPC in your crosshair; pin any solo animation from the browser onto it[/*]
[*][b]Vanilla animation library[/b] (optional install): thousands of Starfield's own clips, humans plus 27 creature species, browsable and playable[/*]
[*]Synced multi-actor [b]GLTF / GLB / .af[/b] playback on one shared clock[/*]
[*]JSON [b]scene graphs -[/b] nodes, cues, actions, branching; no scripting needed[/*]
[*]Engine-native [b]Wwise[/b] audio that rides the game mix, with subtitles[/*]
[*]Actor anchoring, camera/control locks, screen fades, equipment hide/restore[/*]
[*]A [b]Papyrus API[/b] ([font=Courier New]OSF.*[/font]) for quest mods to drive scenes[/*]
[/list]

[center][img]https://staticdelivery.nexusmods.com/mods/4187/images/17457/17457-1782620464-2115394493.png[/img][/center]
[b]Requires:[/b] [url=https://www.nexusmods.com/starfield/mods/3256]Address Library for SFSE[/url] and [url=https://www.nexusmods.com/starfield/mods/17711]OSF UI[/url] (renders the browser, the wheel, the settings menu, and hotkeys - the engine and Papyrus API run without it).

Install with MO2 or Vortex; the installer will offer the animation library and the emote pack - take both. Then in-game:
[list]
[*][font=Courier New]F10[/font] opens the animation browser - pick something, hit LAUNCH.[/*]
[*][font=Courier New]B[/font] opens the emote wheel (aim at an NPC first to emote them instead).[/*]
[*]Hotkeys and settings live in OSF UI's settings menu, under [b]OSF Animation[/b].[/*]
[/list]
No OSF UI? The engine still runs headless for content mods; smoke-test from the console (~):
[code]cgf "OSFTest.SoloScene"   ; play a looping test animation
cgf "OSFTest.Stop"        ; stop it[/code]

[center][img]https://staticdelivery.nexusmods.com/mods/4187/images/17457/17457-1782620464-1671481126.png[/img][/center]
[list]
[*][b]Scene authors:[/b] ship scenes as JSON plus GLB/AF clips. No Papyrus, No scripting. Tag a pack name and your scenes group under it in the browser; tag [font=Courier New]player.emote.*[/font] and solo scenes land on the emote wheel.[/*]
[*][b]Quest mods:[/b] drive scenes from Papyrus via the [font=Courier New]OSF.*[/font] API.[/*]
[/list]
Getting Started, the scene schema, and the API are documented on [url=https://github.com/ozooma10/osf-animation]GitHub[/url].

[center][img]https://staticdelivery.nexusmods.com/mods/4187/images/17457/17457-1782620467-859886682.png[/img][/center]
[list]
[*][b]Deweh[/b] ([url=https://github.com/Deweh/NativeAnimationFrameworkSF]NAF[/url]), the playback/graph base OSF is adapted from[/*]
[*][b]Calaverah[/b] ([url=https://github.com/Calaverah/CALUMI.Animation]CALUMI.Animation[/url]), the .af / skeleton decoder [/*]
[*][b]libxse[/b] ([url=https://github.com/libxse/commonlibsf]CommonLibSF[/url]), the SFSE plugin library OSF is built on [/*]
[*]Plus fastgltf, ozz-animation, zlib, nlohmann/json and miniaudio.[/*]
[/list]

 Source and issue tracker on [url=https://github.com/ozooma10/osf-animation]GitHub[/url], Let me know all your complaints and bugs!
